Create same index on new table.
SQL
Copy code
CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX CI_cff_report_new
ON dbo.cff_report_new(report_date,report_id)
ON ps_cff_report(report_date)
Partition applied here.
STEP 7 — Load Data in Batches
Avoid single huge insert.
Example batch load:
SQL
Copy code
DECLARE @batch INT=100000

WHILE 1=1
BEGIN

INSERT INTO dbo.cff_report_new
SELECT TOP (@batch) *
FROM dbo.cff_report
WHERE report_id NOT IN
(
SELECT report_id FROM dbo.cff_report_new
)

IF @@ROWCOUNT=0 BREAK

END
For very large tables (100M+ rows) use:
Copy code

INSERT WITH TABLOCK
Example
SQL
Copy code
INSERT INTO dbo.cff_report_new WITH (TABLOCK)
SELECT *
FROM dbo.cff_report
This enables minimal logging.
STEP 8 — Recreate Non-Clustered Indexes Dynamically
Generate index DDL:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT
'CREATE INDEX ['+i.name+'] ON dbo.cff_report_new ('+
STRING_AGG(c.name,',')+
')'
FROM sys.indexes i
JOIN sys.index_columns ic
ON i.object_id=ic.object_id AND i.index_id=ic.index_id
JOIN sys.columns c
ON ic.object_id=c.object_id AND ic.column_id=c.column_id
WHERE i.object_id=OBJECT_ID('cff_report')
AND i.index_id>1
GROUP BY i.name
